WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.320
Hi, my name is Barret Schloerke and I'm a software engineer on the Shiny team at RStudio.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:18.600
Today we're going to talk about how plumber and future can be combined to create an asynchronous

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:21.240
web API.

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:24.760
So let's consider an example where we have two R functions.

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:29.400
Each function takes an ID, but the first one will do a fast calculation.

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:34.919
We can think it'll take roughly zero seconds, and the second one will do a slow calculation.

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:38.279
This one will take about 10 seconds.

00:00:38.279 --> 00:00:44.840
Plumber can take these two functions and decorate them using roxygen2-like comments.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:50.279
In this case, both of these functions can be accessed using a git route, but the first

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:57.200
one will be accessed under fast ID, and the second one will be accessed using slow ID.

00:00:57.200 --> 00:00:59.840
Any questions?

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:07.120
The ID will represent the order in which the request was sent, so if ID 1 will be sent

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:09.879
before ID 2.

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:13.000
Let's see how plumber will handle these requests.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:19.000
In the receive stage, the request will be unpacked and be prepped for processing.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.239
In the processing stage, we will execute the user function, your function, such as the

00:01:24.239 --> 00:01:27.680
fast calculation or the slow calculation.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:34.239
And then finally, once they are done, we will bundle them up in the respond stage.

00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:39.000
The receive and respond stage must be handled by plumber, because that is very specific

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.019
plumber logic.

00:01:42.019 --> 00:01:46.360
So let's look at an example where we have four requests that arrive at roughly the same

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:47.800
time.

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:53.959
In order, it'll go a fast, then a slow, then a slow, and then a fast.

00:01:53.959 --> 00:01:57.160
Let's see how these execute.

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:03.160
Fast comes in, is processed really quickly, responded, and then done.

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:09.160
Slow comes in, is received, processed, but processing takes 10 seconds.

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:14.240
It is a long time, a very long time, but that's okay.

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:16.600
That's how long that route takes.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:18.399
And then we'll finally respond.

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:26.399
The second slow route has been waiting patiently, but will also take another 10 seconds to calculate.

00:02:26.399 --> 00:02:28.639
Little long, but it's okay.

00:02:28.639 --> 00:02:30.880
That's how long it takes.

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:33.000
And then finally, it will respond.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.199
And the fast route has been waiting patiently, processes really quickly, and then responds

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:41.320
to its original request.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:48.100
So in total, this will take about 20 seconds.

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:53.119
The first fast route will be processed roughly instantly.

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:58.860
The second request, which was a slow route, will take 10 seconds to execute, and then

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:00.520
it will respond.

00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:06.220
But since R cannot process multiple things at once, slow three will have to wait 10 seconds

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:09.020
before it can be processed.

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:17.660
And finally, fast four had to wait a total of 20 seconds before it could even be ingested.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:22.820
In our current situation, all four requests completed in 20 seconds.

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:26.500
However, we accumulated 30 seconds of wait time.

00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:30.059
Ideally, we would like this to be zero.

00:03:30.059 --> 00:03:35.220
Let's explore how Future can solve this for us.

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:39.080
So here we have our existing Plumber API code.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:46.899
This is what it would look like if we incorporated it with Future.

00:03:46.899 --> 00:03:51.899
Future is an R package made by Henrik, which allows for parallel and distributed computing

00:03:51.899 --> 00:03:57.740
in R. Let's talk about the three lines of code that have been added to our Plumber API.

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:02.820
The first line of code tells Future what plans should be used.

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:05.820
In this case, we're going to use a multi-session plan.

00:04:05.820 --> 00:04:10.220
I'll leave it to you to figure out which plan is best for your situation.

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:15.500
The remaining code is used to tell Plumber that, hey, this expression needs to be calculated

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:18.420
using the Future R package.

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:22.859
This allows for the main R session to not be blocked.

00:04:22.859 --> 00:04:28.420
A point of note, you must return the result of your Future call in your Plumber router

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:30.459
for it to take effect.

00:04:30.459 --> 00:04:34.260
Otherwise, Plumber will not know what's happening.

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:38.739
Let's take a look at the execution time with Plumber and Future.

00:04:38.739 --> 00:04:43.700
With just Plumber alone, it took 20 seconds total, and we had 30 seconds of accumulated

00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:44.700
wait time.

00:04:44.899 --> 00:04:50.220
However, when we add in Future, everything is run immediately.

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:55.739
This allows for the total execution time to only take 10 seconds, and we have zero accumulated

00:04:55.739 --> 00:04:57.140
wait time.

00:04:57.140 --> 00:05:04.700
This is the ideal situation, and everything is responding as fast as possible.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:12.619
Fast 4 responded 20 seconds earlier, and Slow 3 also responded 10 seconds earlier.

00:05:12.619 --> 00:05:14.660
This is a pretty good deal.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:19.059
Let's dive deep to see how this execution is done.

00:05:19.059 --> 00:05:24.579
Plumber has the three steps that we talked about earlier, Receive, Process, and Respond.

00:05:24.579 --> 00:05:27.459
This is all done on the main R session.

00:05:27.459 --> 00:05:30.899
Only one route can be there at a time.

00:05:30.899 --> 00:05:37.540
Future, however, can launch multiple R sessions, and we'll call them Worker 1 and Worker 2.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:42.619
In our use case, we're only going to be using them in the Processing step.

00:05:42.619 --> 00:05:48.459
So we must receive and respond from the main Plumber R session, but we can offload the

00:05:48.459 --> 00:05:53.019
Processing to the Future Workers.

00:05:53.019 --> 00:05:56.100
Let's watch to see how this goes.

00:05:56.100 --> 00:06:00.140
Fast comes in, it is processed, and we respond.

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:01.140
Nothing new.

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:02.140
No surprise.

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:05.380
Slow 2 is offloaded immediately to Worker 1.

00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:10.000
Since the main session is free, then Slow 3 can be offloaded to Worker 2.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.679
This allows Fast 4 to be processed and respond immediately.

00:06:14.679 --> 00:06:17.440
Once Slow 2 is done, it can respond.

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:21.239
Same with Slow 3.

00:06:21.239 --> 00:06:27.160
That's a lot faster and a lot more going on, but in the end, we have no wait time.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:29.760
Let's look at that again.

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:37.519
This allows Fast 4, since it's not being blocked by Slow 2 or Slow 3, Fast 4 can respond immediately

00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:40.160
at the 0 second mark.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:45.399
And since we can do things in parallel, Slow 3 is also being processed at the same time

00:06:45.399 --> 00:06:47.359
as Slow 2.

00:06:47.359 --> 00:06:50.100
Both of these do not block the main R session.

00:06:50.100 --> 00:06:52.079
This is ideal.

00:06:52.079 --> 00:06:58.079
However, there are some limitations to what we can do with Plumber in the future.

00:06:58.079 --> 00:07:03.160
One, you have to manually add your Future Call wherever you deem appropriate.

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:08.760
This is because adding the Future Call adds a little bit of execution time to each route.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:15.040
Now, if your execution time is normally in the seconds, and adding a quarter of a second

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:19.799
does not mean much to you, then great, I think Future is a perfect candidate for that route.

00:07:19.799 --> 00:07:24.359
However, if adding a quarter of a second to your execution time dramatically increases

00:07:24.359 --> 00:07:28.880
it, maybe adding Future is maybe not the best idea, and instead we'll just keep it in the

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:31.019
main R session.

00:07:31.019 --> 00:07:35.959
The other one we have to remember is that processing power is finite and memory is finite.

00:07:35.959 --> 00:07:40.579
We cannot necessarily launch 100,000 workers on one laptop.

00:07:40.579 --> 00:07:44.980
That would be a little bit of overload, either with processing power or the memory.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:49.420
One of the two will limit what you can do on your machine.

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:53.700
I'd like to thank you for listening in on how Plumber and Future can be integrated to

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:56.540
help you create an asynchronous web API.

00:07:56.540 --> 00:08:00.779
Remember, offload your slow routes using Plumber expressions.

00:08:00.820 --> 00:08:06.779
This will help keep your main Plumber worker available to process incoming requests.

00:08:06.779 --> 00:08:07.779
Thank you.

